    en: "NY makes it illegal for a business to advertise a product at a low price to lure customers in and then refuse to sell that product or push them into a more expensive one. The rule is in NY General Business Law section 396 and is also covered by the broader deceptive-practices statute at GBL 349. Violators face misdemeanor charges, civil penalties from the NY Attorney General, and private suits by consumers. Common bait-and-switch scenes include car dealerships advertising a car at a low price that turns out to be sold or unavailable, electronics stores advertising a TV with no inventory, and mattress stores advertising a model they then steer customers away from. The advertised item must be available in reasonable quantities at the advertised price, or the seller must offer a clear rain check."
